A Data Driven Approach to US Medical School Admissions

This website is meant to give you a somewhat contrarian approach to medical school admissions: a data-driven approach. I am obligated to note that numbers are not everything, but youve probably had a few hundred people tell you that already. A couple notes before we start: this is an analysis of US MD medical schools in the MSAR database. Several schools have data that doesnt really tell the whole story, lets go through a few outliers.

Brown (Alpert): With a large BS/MD class, admissions rates appear high and the amount of volunteering and shadowing low. Do not be fooled. These numbers are likely skewed by the __% of students with guaranteed admission to medical school from the day they step on Brown undergrad who decide to skip these experiences.

Northeast Ohio (NEOMED): Founded in 1973, honestly, Im not sure what exactly is going on over at NEOMED. Just in 2017, 24% of matriculants participated in shadowing. These numbers have risen to 10th percentile numbers in 2020, but honestly Im not sure if this is because of the large BSMD and Early Assurance numbers (__% of the class) or just bad data reporting.

Puerto Rican Schools: By no means an expert in these schools. Im gonna skip these. A guide by someone knowledgable about these schools would be some quality content for the subreddit.

Last disclaimer before we dive in: Why am I doing this? It is not to help future applicants get into medical school. If you havent realized that medical school admissions is a zero-sum game, well, I hate to tell you, the number of spots in medical schools does not vary with how competent and accomplished the pool of applicants is. The same goes for the MCAT, the same goes for CASPER. All have a fixed number of winners. Whether this guide exists or not, the same number of students will be donning a white coat in the fall. This guide is being written for two core reasons: 1. To give data-driven, evidence-based students a leg up in the admissions process. 2. To reduce bloat and expenses in the medical school application process. This is here to help people refine their school lists, send out higher-yield applications to schools that fit, and hopefully, fewer applications. Less applications = Less money spent by students and less staff needed in medical school admissions departments.

Enough of that nonsense, lets dive in.

Medical School Data

Experiences

Community Service

Creighton, Utah, Oakland, and Houston all find themselves above the 90% clip here. On the lower end, South Carolina-Columbia, Oklahoma, and Toldeo hover around 70%. A notable T20 school finds itself in the bottom 5% here: Icahn School of Medicine (71.5%), although this can probably be chalked up to Icahns Early Assurance Program.

Military

The vast majority of schools have military experience in somewhere between 0.3% and 2.5% of their class. There are a couple outliers on each end. USUHS (34.8%), East Tennessee State, Washington State, Marshall, Dartmouth, UNLV, UTHSC, all have above 3% military classes. On the other hand, Creighton and Saint Louis havent matriculated a single student with military experience in the last four years. Perhaps, they dont get many military applicants or perhaps there is some reason military students choose other schools. It could be random chance, remember that the vast majority of schools are bringing in only 1 or 2 military students per year. This is a perfect opportunity to take a look beyond the numbers by looking at UTSA-Long. With a 1.5% military matriculant rate per year, they fall in the 50th-75th percentile. However, take a peek at their website or SDN reviews and youll find Long as programs in military medicine and prides itself on being in San Antonio, the military center of the US. Always supplement data with subjective research as well.

Shadowing

Formal shadowing is a borderline hard requirement at the Mississippi, Utah, FIU, South Alabama, and Nova Southeastern. On the other hand, Brown, UC Riverside, and UC Davis are far more lenient about it with less than 70% of their matriculants having shadowed.

Clinical Volunteering

Rush, Oakland, UCLA take the top three spots here. The UC System as a whole tends to put high value on clinical volunteering as UCLA, Irvine, UC Davis, and UCSF all land in the top 10. On the other hand, lower tier state schools and Puerto Rican schools put a smaller emphasis on this. Brown is notable at the bottom, but that can likely be attributed to the massive BS/MD program that can skip shadowing and clinical volunteering.

Clincial Work

After the Puerto Rican schools and Northeast Ohio, this might as well be an inverted USNWR list. Virtually every T20 school finds itself in the bottom quartile, with UCSF, UCLA and Case Western being some notable exceptions above the 25th percentile.

Research

This might as well be a USNWR list as well. Here ae some schools that put a large focus on research that arent T20 schools: Virginia Tech, Carle Illinois, Utah. Compare this list with a USNWR and youll see that some schools care a great deal about research even if their USNWR research rank doesnt show it: Stony Brook, Einstein, Maryland.

I wont go into the actual median and percentile data here. You can go ahead and read that for yourself in the attached spreadsheet. What I will do here is point out what some of these data points can tell you about what is going on in the admissions office.

Point of Focus #1: Difference Between Accepted and Matriculated MCAT - Theory: Schools with large differences between the caliber of student whom they accept and who show up to campus on Day 1 are whiffing on many above average students (metric wise). For whatever reason high MCAT students arent matriculating, but perhaps this shows us that they are willing to take swings on students who are out of their league

  • This grouping of schools below shoot their shot to try to land the cream of the crop. Some call them stat whores. All you high stat applicants who are trying to find schools who emphasize stats and avoid being yield-protected should have your eyes open.

  • Schools with minimal difference between accepted and matriculated 90th percentile MCAT are telling us one of two things: 1) the students they accept end up matriculating because they are that good (NYU, Mayo), or 2) they dont offer acceptances to students who they think are out of their league stat wise (Drexel, Einstein).

Schools with a high difference between Accepted 90th Percentile and Matriculated 90th Texas Tech El Paso (7) and East Tennessee State (6) shoot their shot. Think of these schools as the Russell Westbrooks of medical schools. They take a million shots in the hopes that some of them go in.

Some other schools show little to no difference in the students they recruit and the students who matriculate. Think of these schools as Steph Curry: when they take a shot its probably going in. Or perhaps Naz Mitrou-Long. Never heard of him? He took one shot in the NBA and made it. Maybe these schools take their high-percentage shot and call it a day, forget the half court shots that would ruin that beautiful shooting percentage.

Notable Schools: NYU Grossman, WashU, Mayo, Harvard, Mississippi

Interview and Acceptance Rates

The whole purpose of the previous six posts is to help you identify schools that you are a target candidate for. Lets take high percentage swings to maximize your return on applications. Do not be the person who shoots 100 inefficient shots from a machine gun. Be a sniper. Shoot highly efficient shots. Youll thank yourself when you spend less money on apps and waste less time writing secondaries you dont care about. Adcoms should thank you for not wasting their time too.

There are 154 schools in the US and Puerto Rico. I will be mentioning a lot of them here. Perhaps the best way to attack this first is to identify schools that are low-yield. By low-yield I do NOT mean high number of applications like most other posts that toss around the term around here and SDN. Low-yield in this context means that an application has a below average chance of yielding an acceptance. Low-yield means applying to Brown, or deciding to apply to one T20 school and picking Stanford.

I will say this one last time, if you havent read the earlier posts in this series

Remember in Part VI where I mentioned that those acceptance rates were hypothetical rates for an average applicant at each pool? Well how do we know what an average applicant is at Harvard? What does the average applicant look like at UC Riverside?

Optimizing a School List

There are several goals we can try to achieve with a school list.

  • Admission to a medical school
  • Minimizing Writing Time
  • Minimizing Expenses Incurred
  • Maximizing Chances of a Financially Plausible School

Acceptance Rates

IS Admissions

OOS Admissions

Acceptance rate is a rather complex calculation. At the most basic level, acceptance rate is simply

\(General Acceptance Rate = \frac{Total Acceptances}{Applications}\)

Of course, acceptance data is hard to find, and not all schools publish acceptance data. As a result, I pulled Post II rates from SDN user TheDataKing and used them to estimate raw acceptance numbers. Schools without a Post II rate were projected to have a Post II rate of 51.63% and 46.71% for in-state and out-of-state applicants respectively. This is simply the median of reported Post II rates. Understand that the projections for these schools may be wildly off-base considering Post II rates can range from 23% to 90%.

With these acceptance numbers and data on MDPHD, ED, BSMD, and EA applicants the following acceptance rate probably estimates the acceptance rate of an average MD-only applicant:

\(Adjusted Acceptance Rate = \frac{(Acceptances - MDPHD Matriculants - ED Matriculants - EA Matriculants - BSMD Matriculants)}{(Applications - MDPHD Applications - ED Matriculants - EA Matriculants - BSMD Matriculants)}\)

The keen among you will instantly note that this equation makes some flawed assumptions: * It uses MDPHD, ED, EA, and BSMD matriculants, not acceptances. For ED applicants we can assume this is true, after all an accepted student means a matriculated student in the ED world. For EA and BSMD students this is a slightly flawed assumption. For MDPHD students it is very flawed to assume that all students accepted to a school matriculate there. Alas, this is * In addition, in the bottom of the equation we assume that ED Matriculants = ED Applications, EA Matriculants = EA Applications, and BSMD Matriculants = BSMD Applications. This is probably valid for EA and BSMD students as only students who are formally accepted into these programs will end us submitting an AMCAS application. However, it is quite clear that not all ED applicants end up matriculating. We can only assume that the difference between ED Applications and ED Matriculants is small enough to neglect.

Regardless, this equation gives us a more specific acceptance rate for M.D.only acceptances. Look how much the acceptance rate changes for schools with large BSMD or EA classes (Brown, Sinai, etc). Adjusted Acceptance Rate will give you a much more specific acceptance rate to your situation.

We can also further subset acceptance rates into male and female acceptance rates with data from AAMC Table XX. We are given gender proportions of applicant pools which allows us to determine how many males and females applied to a given school. We also have data about the gender makeup of the matriculants. If we assume that the accepted student pool has the same gender makeup as the matriculant pool, we can calculate acceptance rates for males and females.

We can go ever DEEPER. Not all applicants who submit an application will finish it. What percentage of applicants finish their secondary application is very sparsely reported. Some data points exist in this SDN thread, chiefly that Johns Hopkins has a rate of 73%, Georgetown a rate of 76%, Miami and Duke a rate of ~50%. Outside of these data points, we can speculate that rates probably vary based on length and cost of the secondary application, ranging anywhere from 50% at schools with the lengthiest secondaries like Duke and Miami to 90+% at schools like UTSA-Long with no secondary and no fee. Multiplying this percentage by the number of primary applications will give us a new number of applications to divide acceptances by. Well call this new acceptance rate the True Acceptance Rate

A Flowchart for School List

US M.D.School List Primer

The average medical student applies to 17 schools as of 2020. There are 150 US MD schools to pick from, and a couple more additional programs not classified as their own medical schools (Cleveland Clinic, Mayo Clinic AZ, Charles Drew, etc.) but applying to all 150 would be a colossal waste of time and money. As a result, most students take the approach of picking anywhere from 10-30 schools and ignoring the rest. This guide is to serve as a flowchart of sorts to help you build a school list not by starting with a list of zero and picking 17 schools, but rather, starting with a list of 150 and whittling it down to 17.

First off, you likely have 1-2 medical schools in your state, maybe even 10+ if you live in Texas, California, or New York. Well put those schools to the side and focus on out of state schools for this portion of the guide. We will begin with schools that the vast majority of students should not bother even thinking about. If you have a relative on an admission committee at one of these places, or attend their undergraduate schools, then perhaps an exception can be made.

On Medical School Admissions

I will preface this by saying that if you have not taken interviews, it may be ideal for you to not read forward. For the same reason that it is not beneficial to know that box-checking works, it is not beneficial for you to understand the games medical schools play. If anything this may make you more cynical and it is probably better for you to just drink the Kool-aid they serve until you are in medical school. Then drink the Kool-Aid until you get into residency. You can stop drinking the Kool-Aid in your 30s when you finish residency.

Okay, you didnt turn around. Consider this to be a set of journals. A document containing all the ponderings of a college senior applying to medical school. Ill try my best not to talk about anything that is already pretty mainstream, that would be a waste of your time. Consider this to be a critique of the state of affairs of the medical school admissions process by a serial SDN reader and game theorist.

Understanding the Macro

There are 150 US MD medical schools in the country. Id say there may be a few serial SDN users, perhaps a premed advisor or two who are less interpersonal and more game theory driven, and a few admissions deans who truly understand the macro picture. Most people who go into admissions, and medicine in general, arent concerned about what the rest of the medical school landscape looks like.

100 Variants of Vanilla and Misguided Praise

When it comes down to it, virtually all medical schools are the same. The vast majority of schools have some variation of a 1 or 1.5 year curriculum. The vast majority of schools are pass/fail pre-clinical. Yet, premeds and admissions committees alike spend an incredible amount of time and resources trying to convince others and themselves that they are not.

Ive taken interviews at roughly 25 schools ranging from the top schools in the country, to mid-level private institutions, to lower ranked public state schools. Here are a couple sales pitches that come up at the vast majority of interviews:

Pass/Fail Status 1.5 Year Preclinical Regular revision of curriculums Outstanding Match Lists Scholarly Concentrations Community involvement Free Clinics Level 1 Trauma Centers Diversity, trendy food scenes, etc. Global health opportunities Collaborative Environment

Ill break down each of these sales pitches and why they should mean absolutely nothing to 98% of you. But first, Ill break down the one sales pitch that is the unanimous, go-to pitch by student panels and interviewers across the country: the people and the culture are different here.

Take one interview at school X and you might be impressed by the amazing people, culture and friendliness of school X. Take five interviews and you might have new faith in humanity as youll realize that every corner of the globe must have incredible people, culture and friendliness. At some point, with enough interviews and a cynical enough attitude, one will inevitably ask: why do all of these people believe that the people at their institution are so much better?

I propose two explanations: one where a person genuinely believes so and one where cognitive dissonance dictates that they might as well believe it. Perhaps it is the case that a student who tells you that people at their institution are so incredibly friendly and amazing genuinely believes so. But what is their frame of reference? Most medical students only attend one school and have no actual idea of what another medical school is like. Thus when a student of this sort tells you that the culture is great and the people are fun, this information can largely be ignored. A second, more cynical view of this phenomena is that many students will tell you that their medical school is amazing out of a need to justify their choice. Since very few students and faculty actually have a macro understanding of the current medical school affairs, they actually have no idea if the people/culture are better at their school or another. This naturally produces some dissonance. Why would I, a rational and smart person, choose an environment that was less fun and optimal. I either am a) stupid, and made the wrong medical school decision or b) the environment I am in was actually the best decision for me. Most people end up choosing the latter, hence why most people are adamant that they made the right college decision and couldnt see themselves anywhere else

On Pass/Fail Status

For whatever reason, premeds still rave about this, almost as much as admissions committees. Yet most premeds dont realize that pass/fail is the status quo. Ill repeat that: A pass/fail pre-clinical is the rule, not the exception. So why do so many premeds beat their chest over this? Part of the reason is that premeds typically lag a few years

In the vast majority of cases, people compare their experience with their vague conception of the prototypical medical school. Most people happen to imagine medical school as a hellish place of incredible competition and burnout. When they get to medical school and realize that people arent spitting in their agar plates, the

On Level 1 Trauma Centers

You may hear the pitch that School X is the only Level 1 trauma center in the region, so we see the sickest of the sick. That sounds very cool. Until you realize that there are 232 trauma centers that can be classified as a Level 1 trauma center in the US. And guess what? It seems the majority of medical schools are associated with one. It would be foolish of you to go to a school because of its level 1 trauma center, as it is highly likely that

On Outstanding Match Lists

Honestly I cant comment much on this. I just hear it at a lot of low-mid tier schools. Youll rarely hear this at top schools, they dont need to say it.

But Why

Weve established that the vast majority of the things presented on websites and interview days are what boils down to marketing nonsense. Part of the reason any of these things exist is that schools simply dont recognize that they are not as unique as they think they are. Most medical schools dont compare themselves to the average medical school. Some compare themselves to what medical school used to be like 20 years ago. Some compare themselves to their perception of what the average medical school is, which is almost always pessimistic. But almost nobody speaks about themselves relative to the average school, and certainly noone speaks of themselves relative to the top medical schools.

Yet, what I believe the primary reason is, is the urge/need on part of medical school admissions to say something.

Winning More

In the wise words of SDN user KnightDoc, once the cycle starts, everyone just wants an interview. Then they just want an acceptance anywhere. Then they just want some financial aid. Then they just want more financial aid. Id wager that 90% of applicants set out applying with the sole goal of getting an acceptance. Why not take a little foresight and craft your school list in such a way to maximize your shot at getting financial aid as well?

Truth be told, some schools are amazing with financial aid. Other schools are atrocious with it. Some schools wont even give you a financial aid offer until after you enroll. An acceptance at NYU is not the same as an acceptance at Temple and it has nothing to do with prestige.

Heres a short list of schools who do not give out financial aid offers + Stony Brook + Temple

Now, take a moment to think, in what scenario does someone matriculate somewhere without knowing their financial aid package? It boils down to one of the following: 1. They dont have any other acceptances 2. Paying full tuition at this school is cheaper than any other financial package theyve recieved 3. Money doesnt matter to this applicant
